## Economic Causes

### British Debt and Taxation

The enormous debt from the French and Indian War compelled Britain to seek revenue from the colonies. The British government imposed taxes on essential goods and legal documents, which directly affected the economic activities of colonists, including merchants, farmers, and artisans.

The economic impact was severe:

- The Sugar Act and Townshend Acts increased the cost of imported goods.
- The Stamp Act taxed everyday transactions, affecting nearly all colonists.
- The Currency Act restricted colonial currency issuance, destabilizing local economies.
- The Tea Act monopolized tea sales, harming colonial merchants.

These measures disrupted colonial trade and livelihoods, provoking economic hardship and resentment ([Price, 1992](https://www.ncpedia.org/anchor/revolutionary-north-carolina); [123 Help Me, n.d.](https://www.123helpme.com/political-social-and-economic-causes-of-the-american-revolution-view.asp?id=117926)).

### Colonial Economic Autonomy and Smuggling

Prior to strict enforcement, many colonists engaged in smuggling to avoid taxes, especially on molasses and sugar. The Molasses Act of 1733, though not heavily enforced initially, laid the groundwork for a colonial economy increasingly independent of British control. The crackdown on smuggling by customs officials under the Sugar Act and subsequent laws was perceived as an infringement on colonial economic freedom ([Revolutionary-War-and-Beyond.com, 2017](https://www.revolutionary-war-and-beyond.com/revolutionary-war-causes.html)).

