## Social and Ideological Causes

### Enlightenment Ideas and Liberal Political Thought

The American Revolution was influenced by Enlightenment principles, particularly the writings of John Locke, who argued for natural rights and the right to rebel against unjust governments. These ideas inspired colonial leaders and the general populace to question the legitimacy of British rule and assert their rights to self-governance and liberty ([PapersBureau.com, n.d.](https://papersbureau.com/what-are-the-political-and-economic-causes-of-the-american-revolution/)).

### Colonial Identity and Desire for Self-Government

Over time, the colonists developed a distinct identity separate from Britain. They had established their own legislative bodies and legal systems, fostering a sense of political autonomy. The imposition of British control was seen as a threat to their established way of life and freedoms.

### Social Divisions and Internal Conflicts

Within the colonies, populations were divided among Patriots (Whigs), Loyalists (Tories), and neutrals. In North Carolina, for example, about one-third supported independence, one-third remained loyal to Britain, and one-third were neutral or indifferent ([Price, 1992](https://www.ncpedia.org/anchor/revolutionary-north-carolina)). This division led to internal conflicts and violence during the war.

---

## Key Events Escalating to War

### Boston Massacre (1770)

Tensions escalated when British soldiers fired on unarmed colonists in Boston, killing five men. This event was widely publicized and fueled anti-British sentiment ([Revolutionary War Reading Comprehension](https://www.k12reader.com/worksheet/the-revolutionary-war/)).

### Boston Tea Party (1773)

In protest against the Tea Act, colonists disguised as Native Americans boarded British ships and dumped tea into Boston Harbor. This act of defiance led to harsh British reprisals known as the Coercive Acts ([Price, 1992](https://www.ncpedia.org/anchor/revolutionary-north-carolina)).

### Formation of the Continental Congress (1774)

In response to British policies, colonies convened the First Continental Congress to coordinate resistance. This body laid the groundwork for unified colonial action ([Price, 1992](https://www.ncpedia.org/anchor/revolutionary-north-carolina)).

### Battles of Lexington and Concord (1775)

The first military engagements between colonial militias and British troops marked the outbreak of armed conflict. The "shot heard round the world" symbolized the start of the Revolutionary War ([Price, 1992](https://www.ncpedia.org/anchor/revolutionary-north-carolina)).

---

## The War and Its Aftermath

### Declaration of Independence (1776)

The colonies formally declared independence, asserting their right to self-governance and freedom from British rule. This declaration was a direct outcome of the accumulated grievances and ideological shifts ([Price, 1992](https://www.ncpedia.org/anchor/revolutionary-north-carolina)).

### Establishment of New Governments

Colonies, including North Carolina, drafted new constitutions emphasizing popular sovereignty, separation of powers, and individual rights. These documents reflected revolutionary ideals and a rejection of monarchical authority ([Price, 1992](https://www.ncpedia.org/anchor/revolutionary-north-carolina)).

