## Summary Table of Causes

| Cause Category      | Specific Causes/Events                                   | Impact/Significance                                  |
|---------------------|---------------------------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
| Political           | Lack of representation, Parliamentary acts              | Eroded colonial self-governance, sparked protests   |
| Economic            | War debt taxation, trade restrictions, currency control | Damaged colonial economies, fostered resentment     |
| Social/Ideological  | Enlightenment ideas, colonial identity                   | Inspired desire for liberty and self-rule           |
| Key Incidents       | Boston Massacre, Boston Tea Party, Lexington & Concord  | Catalyzed armed conflict and unity among colonies   |

---

## Conclusion

The Revolutionary War was fought due to a complex interplay of political, economic, social, and ideological factors. Central to the conflict was the colonists' rejection of British taxation without representation and the desire to protect their economic interests and political freedoms. Enlightenment ideals and a growing colonial identity further fueled the movement toward independence. While the war was costly and divisive, it ultimately resulted in the establishment of a new nation founded on principles of popular sovereignty and individual rights.

This analysis underscores that the war was not merely a reaction to taxation but a profound struggle over governance, rights, and identity. The legacy of the Revolution continues to influence democratic ideals worldwide.

